{
  "texts": [
    "A larger N provides more flexibility in choosing other parameters of the concrete FHE scheme.",
    "For example, in the SIMD schemes it allows for a higher multiplicative depth, reducing the number of bootstrapping operations that are needed, while in CGGI/DM schemes it allows to evaluate a larger table look-up during bootstrapping.",
    "It also allows to have a smaller d num in hybrid key switching, which speeds up the key switching operation.",
    "Another important consideration is that the size of all large keys is linearly proportional to N.",
    "If key size is a concern, for example, due to input/output or communication bandwidth limitations, log 2 (q) could be minimized to keep N as small as possible."
  ]
}